{
  "id": "break_continue",
  "title": "JS Break & Continue",
  "group": "JS Loops",
  "content": [
    { "type": "h1", "text": "JavaScript Break and Continue" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "The break and continue statements give you control over loop execution. break exits the loop entirely, while continue skips the current iteration and moves to the next one." },

    { "type": "h2", "text": "The break Statement" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "The break statement terminates the current loop immediately. Execution continues with the first statement after the loop." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "break Statement", "code": [
      "// Exit loop when value is found",
      "for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {",
      "  if (i === 5) {",
      "    console.log(\"Found 5, stopping!\");",
      "    break;",
      "  }",
      "  console.log(i);",
      "}",
      "// Output: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, \"Found 5, stopping!\"",
      "",
      "// Search in array",
      "let numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50];",
      "let target = 30;",
      "let found = false;",
      "",
      "for (let i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {",
      "  if (numbers[i] === target) {",
      "    found = true;",
      "    console.log(\"Found \" + target + \" at index \" + i);",
      "    break;",
      "  }",
      "}",
      "// Output: \"Found 30 at index 2\""
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "The continue Statement" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "The continue statement skips the rest of the current iteration and jumps to the next one. The loop continues running." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "continue Statement", "code": [
      "// Skip even numbers",
      "for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {",
      "  if (i % 2 === 0) {",
      "    continue; // Skip even numbers",
      "  }",
      "  console.log(i);",
      "}",
      "// Output: 1, 3, 5, 7, 9",
      "",
      "// Skip specific items",
      "let fruits = [\"apple\", \"\", \"banana\", null, \"cherry\"];",
      "for (let fruit of fruits) {",
      "  if (!fruit) {",
      "    continue; // Skip empty/null values",
      "  }",
      "  console.log(fruit);",
      "}",
      "// Output: apple, banana, cherry"
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "break vs continue" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "The key difference: break exits the entire loop, while continue only skips the current iteration. Choose based on whether you want to stop or skip." },
    { "type": "table", "rows": [
      ["Feature", "break", "continue"],
      ["Effect", "Exits the loop entirely", "Skips to next iteration"],
      ["Code after it", "Not executed (exits loop)", "Not executed (this iteration)"],
      ["Loop continues?", "No", "Yes"],
      ["Use case", "Stop searching after finding", "Skip unwanted items"]
    ]},
    { "type": "example", "title": "break vs continue Side by Side", "code": [
      "console.log(\"--- Using break ---\");",
      "for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {",
      "  if (i === 3) break;",
      "  console.log(i);",
      "}",
      "// Output: 1, 2",
      "",
      "console.log(\"--- Using continue ---\");",
      "for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {",
      "  if (i === 3) continue;",
      "  console.log(i);",
      "}",
      "// Output: 1, 2, 4, 5"
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "Labeled Statements" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "Labels allow you to break or continue outer loops from inside nested loops. A label is an identifier followed by a colon before a loop statement." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Labeled break and continue", "code": [
      "// Labeled break: exit outer loop",
      "outer: for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {",
      "  for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {",
      "    if (i === 1 && j === 1) {",
      "      console.log(\"Breaking outer loop\");",
      "      break outer;",
      "    }",
      "    console.log(\"i=\" + i + \", j=\" + j);",
      "  }",
      "}",
      "// Output: i=0,j=0  i=0,j=1  i=0,j=2  i=1,j=0  Breaking outer loop",
      "",
      "// Labeled continue: skip to next outer iteration",
      "outer2: for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {",
      "  for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {",
      "    if (j === 1) {",
      "      continue outer2;",
      "    }",
      "    console.log(\"i=\" + i + \", j=\" + j);",
      "  }",
      "}",
      "// Output: i=0,j=0  i=1,j=0  i=2,j=0"
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "break in Nested Loops" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "Without labels, break only exits the innermost loop. To exit multiple levels, use labels or restructure your code using functions with return." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Nested Loop Patterns", "code": [
      "// Without label: break only exits inner loop",
      "for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {",
      "  for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {",
      "    if (j === 1) break; // Only breaks inner loop",
      "    console.log(\"i=\" + i + \", j=\" + j);",
      "  }",
      "}",
      "// Output: i=0,j=0  i=1,j=0  i=2,j=0",
      "",
      "// Alternative: use a function with return",
      "function findValue(matrix, target) {",
      "  for (let i = 0; i < matrix.length; i++) {",
      "    for (let j = 0; j < matrix[i].length; j++) {",
      "      if (matrix[i][j] === target) {",
      "        return { row: i, col: j }; // Exits both loops",
      "      }",
      "    }",
      "  }",
      "  return null;",
      "}",
      "",
      "let grid = [[1, 2], [3, 4], [5, 6]];",
      "console.log(findValue(grid, 4)); // { row: 1, col: 1 }"
    ]},

    { "type": "note", "text": "Labels are rarely needed in practice. If you find yourself using labeled breaks frequently, consider refactoring the nested loops into separate functions and using return instead." },

    { "type": "exercise", "question": "What happens when continue is executed inside a for loop?", "options": ["The loop terminates", "The current iteration is skipped", "The next iteration is skipped", "An error is thrown"], "answer": 1 }
  ]
}
